collection.description: This collection features our conversations throughout the State of Maine held with educators, students, community members, and major Maine industry professionals. We are asking what youth will need to thrive personally, civically, and economically in the Maine of 2050. The collection is expanding daily, so check back!
collection.title: Maine ED 2050

highlights.description: schools in general haven't changed as much as our world has in 2023
Preparing kids for life after graduation, beyond academics.
Kids are more tolerant of the diversity amongst students, whether someone needs extra academic help, is struggling emotionally, or with who they are.
Important for students to feel safe to take risks, fail and try again, making a safe community.
Looking at different learning styles, all kids don't fit same box.
Problem at HS of students with very little academic success, getting them to buy in to school to get them to graduation. So many resources, must be a better way

I think we are over estimating how resilient many students and adults are. I think many people are good at putting on a brave face but are falling apart behind the scenes. Let's not lose track of all that was lost by everyone during Covid years, both academically and socially. Rights of passage for students that can never be brought back.
failing middle school and going onto high school

An example is that the current 2nd grade in my building did the K math curriculum last year as 1st graders because we did meet them where they were at after Covid learning but then we jumped straight into 2nd grade curriculum this year, skipping over essential basic math skills. Stronger math students can handle this but any strugglers get really left behind. 
Same for high schoolers who missed so much school due to covid years. My current senior daughter was a freshman when covid hit and so suddenly as a junior had to do midterms etc for the first time without having the experience and practice that freshman and sophomore year would usually bring.Some teachers were better at recognizing that than others.
A truly excellent idea. Unless you are in the school buildings, you have no idea about the reality of what students and adults are dealing with on a daily basis.
knowledge needed by decision makers of classroom experiences
funding is a barrier/obstacle to school evolving
There is a lot to the job of bus driver, more than people understand.
Getting to really know students is the way to engage them.
